label.value: Standard for the Exchange of Nonclinical Data Implementation Guide Version 3.1

value.value: The 3.1 version of the standard for exchange of nonclinical data (SEND) implementation guide.
A part of the respiratory system in multiple species (predominantly avian) which are variably connected with the lung.
An assessment of the opposition to airflow through the respiratory tract on inspiration and/or expiration.
A clinical judgment made based on the apparent volume of gas being inspired or expired.
The period of time between the end of exhalation and the active start of inspiration.
The period of time between the end of inhalation and the active start of expiration.
The amount of time required to reach a specific tidal volume as measured from the start of exhalation.
The recorded time interval between the initiation of exhalation and the time at which no further lung volume reduction occurs.
The volume of gas an individual can forcible exhale from the lungs in one breath.
The recorded time interval between the initiation of inhalation and the point at which no further lung volume expansion occurs.
The average blood pressure reading in the pulmonary artery as calculated through multiple cardiac cycles.
The volume of gas inhaled or exhaled from the lungs during sixty seconds.

A composite lung function endpoint that is composed of peak inspiratory and peak expiratory flows, expiration time, and relaxation time, is used to measure the occurrence and prolongation of apnea periods, and is scaled to inspiratory/expiratory strength to account for breathing variability.
The maximum amount of pressure applied to the lungs during expiration.
The fastest flow rate of gas noted during the inspiratory cycle.
The maximum amount of pressure applied to the lungs during inhalation.
The blood pressure in the pulmonary artery during ventricular relaxation (diastole).

A measure of the lung's ability to stretch and expand, either statically, the change in volume for a given applied pressure, or dynamically, the elasticity of the lung at any given time during the actual movement of air.
The blood pressure in the pulmonary artery during the contraction of the left ventricle of the heart.
An indicator that can be set or unset in order to signal whether the study has been conducted using good laboratory practice standards.
A detectable aggregation of substance in the cytoplasm or nucleus.
This gene is involved in the antimicrobial activity of cytotoxic T-lymphocytes and natural killer cells.

Human GNLY wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 2p11.2 and is approximately 14 kb in length. This allele, which encodes granulysin protein, plays a role in defense responses to microbial infection.
Granulysin (145 aa, ~16 kDa) is encoded by the human GNLY gene. This protein is involved in the antimicrobial activity of cytotoxic granules of cytotoxic T-lymphocytes and natural killer cells.
This gene plays a role in the activation and differentiation of lymphocytes, dendritic cells and endothelial cells.

label.value: Anti-CD3 x Anti-HER-2-Neu Bispecific Monoclonal Antibody/Autologous Lymphocytes/Interleukin-2/Sargramostim

value.value: Human CD48 wild-type allele is located within 1q21.3-q22 and is approximately 33 kb in length. This allele, which encodes CD48 antigen protein, is involved in CD2 signaling.
CD48 antigen (243 aa, ~28 kDa) is encoded by the human CD48 gene. This protein plays a role in both CD2 binding and activation of ligand-dependent signaling pathways.
A set of questions and responses designed to evaluate an individual's self-reported satisfaction with the outcome of treatment.
A set of questions and responses designed to evaluate an individual's self-reported expectations with the outcome of treatment.
This gene is involved in glucose and lipid metabolism.

Human FGF22 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 19p13.3 and is approximately 4 kb in length. This allele, which encodes fibroblast growth factor 22 protein, plays a role in both glucose homeostasis and lipid metabolism.
